Most of the goblins are fairly simple.  There are three problems that you have to keep in mind, however.<br>
First is that the goblins WILL run.  Set your camp spot in an area with an obvious straightaway that you can see down.  That way, if the last mob's health drops faster than you realized, you can still blast it before it gets too far away, and possibly out of sight for a follow-up if you fizzle the first.  If that mob gets out of sight, you're dead.<br>
Second is the goblin wizards.  When I initially came down here, I used a focused fire pet, and it tore through the goblins, shaman included (I spent most of the battle rooted and/or poisoned, but it wasn't too big of a problem).  Then I met my first goblin wizard.  These things are nasty.  Their primary spell seems to be force shock, which both does a rather nasty amount of damage to its target and stuns as well.  Yeah, you've got a nasty DD at your fingertips, but its rather hard to use it when you're stunned.  And hopefully, the mob doesn't pick that time to run off.  It goes without saying - get the air pet.  It'll take more work to bring down the other mobs, but its the only thing that can tackle the wizards.<br>
Third is the way the goblins are distributed.  Sometimes they're by themselves, and other times they're in packs.  Use the Eye of Zomm to scout around before you pull, and make sure you spot all of them.<br>
My favorite camp spot is found behind the gnome castle.  Drop down into the mini courtyard near the gnome vendor, and bind there (You'll have to use a pet to help reach the gnomes.  Just be aware that after you've passed the first few gnomes, but before you reach the castle, there's a jump you'll need to make over lava.  Your pet CANNOT get across here - it apparently falls in and can't get back out.  Plan ahead.).  Then head through the portcullis, across two bridges, to a small slightly open cavern.  There should be a couple of static clockworks and possibly one roaming clockwork.  The advantages of this section are two-fold.  First is that it has enough visibility to allow a nuke if a goblin starts to run.  Second is that its right at the border of the gnome area and the goblin area, so you can easily pull goblins here, and also meditate in safety.  The first few times you pull, you're almost guaranteed to get at least two goblins, so plan ahead.  Make sure you've thoroughly scouted the area before pulling, as well (I got annoyed, and then careless yesterday, and pulled what I thought was a solitary goblin.  Unfortunately, I hadn't seen the little door that led to a small room with four goblins.).  And if you overpull, whatever you do, do NOT run back to the castle.  The gnomes and clockworks will NOT assist you against the goblins, and the last thing you want to do is bring the goblins back to your bind spot (if you bound yourself inside the castle).<br>
And if you're careful, you can actually break the blazing elemental spawn point and camp them for your epic (I did this for a little while).  Its a fairly dull camp, though, as there's only three of them, and it takes them roughly a half hour to respawn.<br>
One other thing.  Sol A usually doesn't attract groups, but it does tend to attract power levelers.  Don't be surprised if you zone in and find a power levelling duo at all of the best spawn points.<br>
